{
  "doc_id": "30808",
  "text": "Upon generation of a new lamellipodium, there was an increase in the local F-actin concentration (Fig. S2 ), which likely led to an increase in contractile forces owing to newly formed actomyosin between the nucleus and the leading edge [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The increased contraction pulled the nucleus toward the newly formed lamellipodium. This finding is in apparent contradiction to previous studies indicating that the nucleus moves away from the leading edge in cells at the boundary of a scratch wound [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . However, a key difference is that in the previous studies, nuclear motion was observed in cells at the edge of a cell monolayer, where cell-to-cell pulling forces are relevant; these forces are absent in isolated cells. If these cell-cell pulling forces are transmitted to the nucleus and exceed the pulling force from the new leading edge, a net rearward motion of the nucleus should occur.",
